{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff19c5a5-0d62-462f-a3e4-7b54f0ed9816","content":"Here's the recommended approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. `kubectl exec` into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --duration 00:00:30 --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n**To get the file off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, you can sidecar the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) image instead — it exposes an HTTP API for on-demand trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- For CPU-specific issues, `--profile cpu-sampling` is the right default. Use `gc-collect` or `gc-verbose` if you suspect memory pressure driving CPU (GC thrashing).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5682bacf-389f-4f26-8b0a-0e4b32ba1387","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":408},"id":"1ce49629-5a31-434e-a551-c129e2f8684d","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:48:25.696Z","parentId":"a5a7ad24-b750-4bc1-8a9a-f6fcdc7c6fa7"}
